<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Acting Secretary of State to
                        the Embassy in the Soviet Union</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1948v04</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d527</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">527</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1948-01-23T14:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1948-01-23T14:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-01-23T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-01-23T14:00:00-05:00" n="527" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d527">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.6111/1–2348: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Soviet Union</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-01-23T14:00:00-05:00">January 23, 1948—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>89. We are holding in NY Customs 19 pieces of recently arrived Soviet chancery
                    supplies in addition 40 pieces mentioned <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 2050 Dec 22.<note n="1" xml:id="d527fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    Please indicate action you wish us to take on these consignments.</p>
                <p>Dept also interested learn whether <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">Fonoff</gloss> has
                    established new customs quota Emb imports for 1948.<note n="2" xml:id="d527fn2">Ambassador Walter Bedell Smith replied in telegram 129 from Moscow on
                        January 24, not printed, that in view of continued difficulties, and with
                        the 1948 customs quota still 900,000 rubles, he requested that the 19 pieces
                        continue to be held (701.6111/1–2448).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
</TEI>
